<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1013,1890]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,1167,1193]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Etymology</emphasis>
:—The species is named after the mythical Czech scientist, dramatist, poet, and writer Jára Cimrman.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1013,1890]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,364,1245,1271]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Observations</emphasis>
:—The life cycle contains several morphologically distinct stages (
<figureCitation box="[1215,1292,1245,1271]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). One was described above, i.e long, gradually tapering, heteropolar filaments (
<figureCitation box="[972,1141,1284,1310]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Figs 1A, B, P</figureCitation>
). The second consists of hormogonia composed of short, isodiametric, barrel-shaped to spherical cells resembling in morphology 
<taxonomicName authority="Vaucher ex Bornet et Flahault (1888: 181)" authorityName="Bornet et Flahault" authorityPageNumber="181" authorityYear="1888" box="[151,748,1361,1387]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Nostocaceae" genus="Nostoc" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,233,1361,1386]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Nostoc</emphasis>
Vaucher ex 
<bibRefCitation author="Bornet, E. &amp; Flahault, C." box="[383,748,1361,1387]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" pagination="177 - 262" refId="ref3727" refString="Bornet, E. &amp; Flahault, C. (1888) Revision des Nostocacees heterocystees contenues dans les principaux herbiers de France. Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Botanique, Septieme serie 7: 177 - 262." type="journal article" year="1888">Bornet et Flahault (1888: 181)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus box="[757,820,1361,1387]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">types</typeStatus>
lacking the sheath (
<figureCitation box="[1062,1154,1361,1387]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Fig. 1E</figureCitation>
). Some cells within the hormogonia grow in size and change their shape to spherical (
<figureCitation box="[902,1041,1400,1426]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Figs 1D, O</figureCitation>
). Cells may sometimes divide in more than one plane (
<figureCitation box="[406,578,1438,1464]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Figs 1L, M, O</figureCitation>
), but never form a true branch. A new filament then germinates from the hormogonia (
<figureCitation box="[319,417,1477,1503]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). The first cell of the filament becomes a heterocyte. The hormogonia with large spherical cells (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[384,474,1516,1542]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
) occur in young cultures only.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1013,1890]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">
Our strain differs from the morphologically similar genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Agardh ex Bornet et Flahault (1886: 345)" authorityName="Agardh ex Bornet et Flahault" authorityPageNumber="345" authorityYear="1886" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Rivulariaceae" genus="Calothrix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[886,998,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Calothrix</emphasis>
Agardh ex 
<bibRefCitation author="Bornet, E. &amp; Flahault, C." pageId="2" pageNumber="38" pagination="323 - 381" refId="ref3649" refString="Bornet, E. &amp; Flahault, C. (1886) Revision des Nostocacees heterocystees contenues dans les principaux herbiers de France. Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Botanique, Septieme serie 3: 323 - 381." type="journal article" year="1886">Bornet et Flahault (1886: 345)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of a terminal hair and frequent false single or double branching (
<figureCitation box="[1203,1380,1593,1619]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" captionTargetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[220,1371,191,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Figs 1G, H, N</figureCitation>
). As notable from 
<figureCitation box="[319,394,1632,1658]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,244,1658,1679]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,191,1637]" captionTargetId="figure-179@4.[153,1434,191,1637]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Phylogenetic analysis based on 16S rDNA sequence with 70 OTUs, using neigbor-joining topology. The support values are given for Neighbor-joining, Maximum likelihood, and Bayesian posterior probabilities. The cut-off values for bootstrap and probability are 50 (0.5 resp). Our reference strain CCALA 1012 (accession number HF912386) is printed in bold. Clusters A and B represent clades with members of the Microchaetaceae family demonstrating heterogeneity of the genus Tolypothrix and the whole family Microchaetaceae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078714/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
, the 16S rRNA sequence of 
<taxonomicName box="[752,1027,1632,1657]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="cimrmanii">
<emphasis box="[752,1027,1632,1657]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Calochaete cimrmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very distant from members of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,314,1670,1696]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Rivulariaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="family">Rivulariaceae</taxonomicName>
and is more related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.J.Lemmermann" authorityYear="1907" box="[591,796,1670,1696]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="family">Microchaetaceae</taxonomicName>
. The most similar are sequences of 
<emphasis box="[1226,1350,1671,1696]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Tolypothix</emphasis>
strains UAM 332, 334, 337 and PCC 7504, but the degree of tapering is significantly lower in these strains. The low degree of tapering itself is one of the key diacritical features of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Kutzing ex Bornet et Flahault (1887: 118)" authorityName="Kutzing ex Bornet et Flahault" authorityPageNumber="118" authorityYear="1887" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Tolypothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1040,1176,1748,1773]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Tolypothrix</emphasis>
Kützing ex 
<bibRefCitation author="Bornet, E. &amp; Flahault, C." pageId="2" pageNumber="38" pagination="51 - 129" refId="ref3688" refString="Bornet, E. &amp; Flahault, C. (1887) Revision des Nostocacees heterocystees contenues dans les principaux herbiers de France. Annales des Sciences Naturelles, Botanique, Septieme serie 5: 51 - 129." type="journal article" year="1887">Bornet et Flahault (1887: 118)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which is accepted in both the botanical (
<bibRefCitation author="Komarek, J. &amp; Anagnostidis, K." box="[964,1371,1786,1812]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" pagination="247 - 345" refId="ref4617" refString="Komarek, J. &amp; Anagnostidis, K. (1989) Modern approach to the classification system of Cyanotphytes 4 - Nostocales. Algological Studies 56: 247 - 345." type="journal article" year="1989">Komárek &amp; Anagnostidis 1989</bibRefCitation>
) and bacteriological (
<bibRefCitation author="Castenholz, R. W." box="[349,558,1825,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" pagination="474 - 487" refId="ref3930" refString="Castenholz, R. W. (2001) General characteristics of the cyanobacteria. In: Boone, D. R. &amp; Castenholz, R. W. (eds.) Bergey's manual of systematic bacteriology, 2 nd edition, volume 1. Springer, New York, pp. 474 - 487." type="book chapter" year="2001">Castenholz 2001</bibRefCitation>
) literatures. From the above mentioned 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kutzing ex Bornet et Flahault" authorityYear="1887" box="[1053,1192,1825,1850]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Tolypothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1053,1192,1825,1850]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Tolypothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
strains, 
<taxonomicName class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="2" pageNumber="38" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="cimrmanii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="38">Calochaete cimrmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs also by living in a significantly different –non-aquatic, high mountain– habitat.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078710" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5078710" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078710/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="39" startId="3.[151,243,1867,1888]" targetBox="[220,1371,191,1831]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1867,2036]" pageId="3" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,261,1867,1888]" pageId="3" pageNumber="39">FIGURE 1</emphasis>
. Morphological variability of the strain CCALA 1012. A. Mature heteropolar filaments. B. detail of well-developed filament with terminal heterocyte. C. A filament germinating from hormogonium with enlarged cells. D, E. Formation of a hormogonium in a filament and hormogonia with enlarging cells. F. Middle part of a mature filament with thin colorless sheath. G. Double branching. H. Single branching. I. Young filament with distinct tapering. J. Swollen bases of mature filaments. K. Shape of the terminal cells. L, M. Enlarged cells in hormogonia dividing in two planes (marked with arrowheads). N. Young growing thallus with single branching. O. Hormogonia and their development after release from mother sheath. M. Well-developed filaments. Bar length = 20 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078714" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5078714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078714/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" startId="4.[151,244,1658,1679]" targetBox="[153,1434,191,1637]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1658,1797]" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,263,1658,1679]" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">FIGURE 2</emphasis>
. Phylogenetic analysis based on 16S rDNA sequence with 70 OTUs, using neigbor-joining topology. The support values are given for Neighbor-joining, Maximum likelihood, and Bayesian posterior probabilities. The cut-off values for bootstrap and probability are 50 (0.5 resp). Our reference strain CCALA 1012 (accession number HF912386) is printed in bold. Clusters A and B represent clades with members of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.J.Lemmermann" authorityYear="1907" box="[524,689,1747,1768]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="family">Microchaetaceae</taxonomicName>
family demonstrating heterogeneity of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kutzing ex Bornet et Flahault" authorityYear="1887" box="[1180,1291,1747,1768]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Tolypothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1180,1291,1747,1768]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">Tolypothrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the whole family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="E.J.Lemmermann" authorityYear="1907" box="[219,385,1776,1797]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="family">Microchaetaceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1844,2025]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,152,409]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">
Comparison of the secondary structures of 16S-23S ITS is of taxonomic importance according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Johansen, J. R. &amp; Casamatta, D. A. &amp; Kastovsky, J." box="[151,421,1883,1909]" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" pagination="283 - 302" refId="ref4438" refString="Johansen, J. R., Kova c ik, L., Casamatta, D. A., Fu c ikova, K. &amp; Kastovsky, J. (2011) Utility of 16 S- 23 S ITS sequence and secondary structure for recognition of intrageneric and intergeneric limits within cyanobacterial taxa: Leptolyngbya corticola sp. nov. (Pseudanabaenaceae, Cyanobacteria). Nova Hedwigia 92 (3 - 4): 283 - 302." type="journal article" year="2011">
Johansen 
<emphasis box="[269,322,1883,1908]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">et al</emphasis>
. (2011)
</bibRefCitation>
. To illustrate specificity and the rate of relatedness of the different morphologically similar taxa included in our study, we provide the two most conserved ITS domains, the D1-D1’ and Box-B helices for 
<taxonomicName box="[294,574,1961,1986]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="cimrmanii">
<emphasis box="[294,574,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">Calochaete cimrmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[592,781,1960,1986]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Tolypothrix" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[592,738,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">Tolypothrix</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
PCC 7504 from cluster “B”, 
<taxonomicName authority="Flechtner et Johansen" authorityName="Flechtner et Johansen" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Spirirestis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="rafaelensis">
<emphasis box="[1159,1436,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">Spirirestis rafaelensis</emphasis>
Flechtner et Johansen
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Flechtner, V. R. &amp; Boyer, S. L. &amp; Johansen, J. R. &amp; DeNoble, M. L." box="[446,741,1999,2025]" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref4125" refString="Flechtner, V. R., Boyer, S. L., Johansen, J. R. &amp; DeNoble, M. L. (2002) Spirirestis rafaelensis gen. et sp. nov. (Cyanophyceae), a new cyanobacterial genus from arid soils. Nova Hedwigia 74: 1 - 24." type="journal article" year="2002">
Flechtner 
<emphasis box="[564,617,1999,2024]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">et al</emphasis>
. (2002: 6)
</bibRefCitation>
WJT-71-NPBG6 from cluster “A”, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1218,1372,1999,2025]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Rivulariaceae" genus="Calothrix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" order="Nostocales" pageId="4" pageNumber="40" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1218,1330,1999,2024]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="40">Calothrix</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
PCC 7507 from a cluster phylogenetically distant from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hauer, Bohunicka &amp; Muhlsteinova" authorityYear="2013" box="[745,879,152,177]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[745,879,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Calochaete</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[896,967,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,244,1729,1750]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,467,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-180@5.[151,1436,467,1708]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Secondary structures of the D1- D1’(row one) and Box-B helices (row two) of strain CCALA 1012 and related strains of types similar either morphologically (Calothrix) or molecularly (members of Microchaetaceae—Tolypothrix and Spirirestis). A, E. Calochaete cimrmanii CCALA 1012. B, F. Tolypothrix sp. PCC 7504. C, G. Spirirestis rafaelensis WJT-71-NPBG6. D, H. Calothrix sp. PCC 7507." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078718" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078718/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It can be clearly seen that 
<taxonomicName class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="species" species="cimrmanii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Calochaete cimrmanii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="PCC" authorityName="PCC" box="[330,527,190,216]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Tolypothrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[330,464,191,216]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Tolypothrix</emphasis>
PCC
</taxonomicName>
7504 are significantly similar in both structures, especially in the basal parts and the bottom halves of the loops (
<figureCitation box="[578,780,229,255]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,244,1729,1750]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,467,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-180@5.[151,1436,467,1708]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Secondary structures of the D1- D1’(row one) and Box-B helices (row two) of strain CCALA 1012 and related strains of types similar either morphologically (Calothrix) or molecularly (members of Microchaetaceae—Tolypothrix and Spirirestis). A, E. Calochaete cimrmanii CCALA 1012. B, F. Tolypothrix sp. PCC 7504. C, G. Spirirestis rafaelensis WJT-71-NPBG6. D, H. Calothrix sp. PCC 7507." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5078718" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5078718/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Figs 3A, B, E, F</figureCitation>
). Concurrently, there are obvious differences in the top portions of the loops, supporting our decision to separate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hauer, Bohunicka &amp; Muhlsteinova" authorityYear="2013" box="[842,977,268,293]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[842,977,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Calochaete</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the traditional genus 
<emphasis box="[1304,1428,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Tolypothix</emphasis>
. The similarity of the secondary structures decreases when comparing 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hauer, Bohunicka &amp; Muhlsteinova" authorityYear="2013" box="[1034,1175,306,331]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Fortiaceae" genus="Calochaete" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1034,1175,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Calochaete</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName box="[1250,1378,306,331]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Microchaetaceae" genus="Spirirestis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1250,1378,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">Spirirestis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a representative of cluster “A” and the most phylogenetically but supposedly morphologically related 
<emphasis box="[151,271,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agardh ex Bornet et Flahault" authorityYear="1886" box="[151,267,384,409]" class="Cyanophyceae" family="Rivulariaceae" genus="Calothrix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" order="Nostocales" pageId="5" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cyanobacteria" rank="genus">Calothrix</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
